        "summary": "The provided document outlines the details of a health insurance plan, specifically a PPO plan for a family, with coverage from January 1, 2025, to December 31, 2025. The plan has an overall deductible of $500 for an individual and $1,000 for a family, which must be met before the plan begins to pay for covered services. However, preventive care and primary care services are covered before the deductible is met, although a copayment or coinsurance may apply. There are also separate deductibles for specific services, such as prescription drug coverage and occupational therapy, which are $300 each.\n\nThe out-of-pocket limit for the plan is $2,500 for an individual and $5,000 for a family for network providers, and $4,000 for an individual and $8,000 for a family for out-of-network providers. Certain expenses, including copayments for certain services, premiums, balance-billing charges, and healthcare that the plan does not cover, are not included in the out-of-pocket limit. Using a network provider will result in lower costs, while using an out-of-network provider will result in higher costs and may involve balance billing.\n\nThe plan requires a referral to see a specialist, and preauthorization is required for certain services, such as specialist visits and outpatient surgery. The plan covers various medical events and services, including office visits, tests, prescription drugs, outpatient surgery, and immediate medical attention, with different copayments and coinsurance rates applying to network and out-of-network providers.\n\nFor example, primary care visits have a $35 copay and 20% coinsurance for network providers, while specialist visits have a $50 copay for network providers. Diagnostic tests have a $10 copay for network providers, and prescription drugs have varying copayments and coinsurance rates depending on the type of drug and provider. Outpatient surgery has a $100/day copay for network providers, and emergency room care has a 20